  "nursesNote": "Generalized anxiety disorder is chronic, excessive worry occurring most days for at least six months that is hard to control and disrupts daily life, often with muscle tension, restlessness, fatigue, irritability, poor concentration, and sleep problems. The nurse builds trust, helps the patient name worries, and teaches coping and relaxation skills (slow breathing, exercise, limiting caffeine). First-line treatment is therapy (CBT) and SSRIs or SNRIs, which take a few weeks to work; buspirone is a non-addictive option that is taken daily (not PRN) and also has a slow onset. Benzodiazepines work fast but are addictive, so they are used only short-term.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Assess the pattern and impact of the worry",
